Comment: I prefer 1.E4 from white to 1.D4

I began playing the Sicilian only after I familiarized myself with the English as white.  Before, I had thought the lines of the Sicilian were too complex, and I favored the French Defence or the Caro Kann.  I would be interested to learn some of the systems where black plays 2.Nc6 or 2.E5 and then Nc6.
I think this is not the most attractive move, closing down the f1-a6 diagonal.
I believe this is a standard move in the Sicilian, just as 2.Nc3 is in the English.
The first inkling that white has in mind to castle queenside and hack black on the kingside.
I am not sure if this is still a standard Sicilian, because I am playing the lines of the English Opening in reverse.
Maybe it would have been better to play for Bb2.
I am not sure, but I think this line may be the infamous Dragon variation.  However, I am still going with lines from the English.
